**Segments**

- Based on type, the venous thromboembolism market can be segmented into deep vein thrombosis (DVT) and pulmonary embolism (PE). DVT occurs when a blood clot forms in a deep vein, usually in the legs. PE, on the other hand, happens when a clot breaks loose and travels to the lungs, causing a blockage in the pulmonary arteries. These segments are crucial for understanding the specific needs and treatment options for patients with venous thromboembolism.

- On the basis of diagnosis, the market can be segmented into blood tests, imaging tests (ultrasound, CT scan, MRI), and D-dimer test. These diagnostic tools help healthcare providers confirm the presence of blood clots in the veins and assess the extent of the condition. Early and accurate diagnosis is key to effective management of venous thromboembolism and reducing the risk of complications.

- In terms of treatment, the venous thromboembolism market can be segmented into anticoagulants (heparin, warfarin, novel oral anticoagulants), thrombolytics, filters (inferior vena cava filters), and compression stockings. Each treatment option aims to prevent the extension of existing clots, reduce the risk of new clots forming, and alleviate symptoms associated with venous thromboembolism.

